- **styled-components**
	- *"styled-components are CSS for JavaScript developers"*
	- VSCode extension for syntax coloring and intellisense: vscode-styled-components##vscodestyledcomponentsext
	- disadvantages
		- in VSCode
			- you can't hover over colors to change them visually
			- reformat doesn't reformat styles
	- look at the styled-component in `Nav.js` for instance, the SiteMessage style has nothing to do with the rest of the application, only with the Nav component and so it is (a) better situated in the component where it is used, and (b) we can more easily make it dynamic with JavaScript, i.e. have it display a different color based on a JavaScript variable
- **dataManager.js**
	- the DataManager was kept simply on purpose to give a basis implementation that can be expanded on
		- advantage: simplicity, i.e. all data for all pages is loaded in the DataManager so each page can use any data source (e.g. `employees`) or any data function (e.g. `getUkEmployees`)
		- disadvantage: possible inefficiency, i.e. *all* data for *every* page needs to be loaded for *each* page, so if a page needs quick-loading data, it still will have to wait for data to be loaded that will be used for other pages
		- possible extensions to address the above issues
			- build a cache in LocalStorage which is refetched e.g. every 10 min / 1 hour / 24 hours, etc. or when the uses clicks "refetch data"
			- use [useMemo](https://edwardtanguay.netlify.app/howtos?id=463)
	- note the employees are loaded from a local JSON file, while customers are loaded from an API
	- child components can get prepared data (e.g. `getLocalUK`) or the raw source data (e.g. `employees`)
	- you can determine the current component that is requesting data with `Component.name`:
		---------------------------------------
		if (Component.name === 'PageEmployees') {
			return !dataLoaded ? <PageLoader/> : <Component {...props} ukEmployees={getUkEmployees()} usaEmployees={getUsaEmployees()} />
		}
		if (Component.name === 'PageCustomers') {
			return !dataLoaded ? <PageLoader /> : <Component {...props} customers={customers} ukCustomers={getUkCustomers()} />
		}
		---------------------------------------
	- and if you base data loading on which component is requesting data, then you can load like this:
		---------------------------------------------
		useEffect(() => {
			setTimeout(async () => {
				if (Component.name === 'PageEmployees') {
					setEmployees(employees);
				}
				if (Component.name === 'PageCustomers') {
					setCustomers(await fetchCustomers());
				}
				setDataLoaded(true);
			}, pageWaitingEmulationInSeconds * 1000);
		}, []);
		---------------------------------------------
	- note that data can be ameliorated/decorated/validated, i.e. new fields can be added, fields can be changed, prepared for easier presentation on the frontend
		-----------------------------
		useEffect(() => {
			employees.map(m => m.fullName = `${m.firstName} ${m.lastName}`);
			setEmployees([...employees]);
		}, [employees]);
		-----------------------------
		- if using TypeScript, this would be the place to make sure the data conformed to interfaces
