- it might be tempting to create a React website which allows a user to log in and see priviliged information
- but one should remember that React is a **frontend** framework
- this means that **all information** is sent to the browser, and then only then is hidden or shown
- to demonstrate this, consider this React site:
	----------------------------------------
	const loggedIn = false;

	function App() {
		return (
			<div className="App">
				<h1>Website</h1>
				<hr />
				{loggedIn && (
					<div>secret</div>
				)}
				<hr />
			</div>
		);
	}

	export default App;
	----------------------------------------
- if you inspect the page's DOM, you will see that the information is indeed not to be found:##reactnotloggedok
- this may tempt you to store sensitive information in conditional rendering on a React site and show it only to logged-in users
- however, if you right-click on your page and **View page source**:##viewpagesourcebrowser
- you will see a small amount of HTML with a link to a JavaScript file:##smallhtmlreact
- click on that link, look around in the file, and you will find your sensitive information in plain text even though it is being blended out in DOM with conditional rendering:##findinforeact

