- Mongoose Custom Queries
	- make previous example of short-books-by-language more flexible
	- Book.js
		---------------------------------
		bookSchema.query.byLanguage = function (language) {
			return this.where('language').equals(language);
		}
		---------------------------------
	- server.js
		--------------------------------
		app.get('/long-books-by-language/:language', async (req, res) => {
			const language = req.params.language;
			const books = await Book.where().byLanguage(language).where('numberOfPages').gt(200);
			res.status(200).json({
				message: `fetched all long books in ${language}`,
				books,
			});
		});		
		--------------------------------
	- note that we have to call a query method on a **where()** or **find()** method
- Mongoose Virtuals
	- create a new field that exists to be sent to the front end, but will not be saved in the database
	- e.g. a field that shows all the info of a book on one line
	- Book.js
		--------------------------
		bookSchema.virtual('bookInfoText').get(function () {
			return `${this.title}, ${this.numberOfPages} pages: ${this.description}`;
		});

		bookSchema.set('toJSON', { virtuals: true });		
		--------------------------
	- now in all routes, this field is automatically in the exported JSON
		- not that for this to be the case, you need the `toJSON` command
		- otherwise the fields will only be available on the object
- Mongoose Middleware
	- background
		- middleware gives you **pre** and **post** hooks on specific commands
		- the most useful commands that have these hooks are **save()**, **validate()**, **remove()**
	- **pre** hook
		- make a whenUpdated field that is written right before object is saved
		- Book.js
			----------------------------------------
			bookSchema.pre('save', function (next) {
				this.whenUpdated = Date.now();
				next();
			});
			----------------------------------------
		- note you have to change the PUT/PATCH routes to use .save() and not updateOne() in order for these hooks to run
			-------------------------------------------
			app.patch('/book/:id', async (req, res) => {
				const id = req.params.id;
				const oldBook = await Book.findOne({ _id: id });
				const book = await Book.findOne({ _id: id });
				Object.entries(req.body).forEach(kv => {
					book[kv[0]] = kv[1];
				}) 
				book.save(); 
				const newBook = await Book.findOne({ _id: id });
				res.status(200).json({
					message: 'patched book with id=' + id,
					oldBook,
					newBook,
				});
			});		
			-------------------------------------------
	- **post** hook
		- after book is saved, log info in the console
		- Book.js
			-----------------------------------
			bookSchema.post('save', function (doc,next) {
				const dt = new Date();
				const timestamp = dt.toISOString();
				console.log(`${timestamp}: updated book "${doc.title}`);
				next();
			});
			-----------------------------------
		- test in save, wherever .save() is used, it will log to the console

