- **==> STEP 4. Move book array of objects to JSON file and import <==**	
	- to increase flexibility, robustness and scalibility of an application, the applications data should be separated from the code
	- the data for our books is currently in our code
	- we want to move the data to a JSON file and then import it 
		- this will be more similar to e.g. fetching the data from an online API or retrieving it from an SQL or MongoDB database
	- convert the JavaScript object to JSON
		- note that there are three main differences between JavaScript objects and JSON
			- JSON must use only double quotes as delimiters of data
			- properties must be enclosed in double quotes
			- JSON does not allow a trailing comma
	- copy the JavaScript array (everything in between the `[]`) and go to: [https://www.convertsimple.com/convert-javascript-to-json](https://www.convertsimple.com/convert-javascript-to-json)
		- click on **unescape**
		- paste JavaScript object array into left textarea box
		- you will see that it is converted to JSON:##converttojsss
	- copy the JSON out, create a file called `src/data/books.json` and paste the JSON content into it
	- in **App.tsx**, delete the variable **books**
	- the site will now get an error because there is no variable **books**
	- at the top of the file, add this line to import your JSON data into the variable **books**
		----------------------------------------------
		import books from './data/books.json';
		----------------------------------------------
	- your site will look the same as before, but your data is now separate from your code, which has the following advantages:
		- your data could be easily changed by another process, e.g. a batch import script
		- your data can be shared with others much more easily
		- if you want to move your data to a MongoDB database, you merely copy-and-paste your JSON into a MongoDB collection, since MongoDB stores data natively in JSON format
