- **what is a headless CMS?**
	- Contentful is a **headless content management system**, or **headless CMS**
		- headless means that it provides only data for a content management system, but not the frontend (head) to display it
		- so it could be considered an online data from which you fetch data (including images) via REST and GraphQL
		- MongoDB Atlas is also an online database, but you would never have a e.g. non-developer employee log into MongoDB Atlas to update the data
			- yet this is possible with Contentful, e.g. **a non-technical person could by taught how to log into Contentful, add new events, upload images, and these would appear instantly on the website**
		- WordPress is an example of a CMS, but it is not headless
			- WordPress comes with the backend and frontend (head) which can't be separated
			- Contentful, on the other hand, provides data which could be fetched from various frontends, e.g. websites, smartphone apps, etc.
