- **implement useContext**
	- to get useContext set up, we will implement it with a simple variable **siteTitle** that we will display on two pages
	- **components/AppContext.tsx**
		------------------------------------------
		import { createContext } from 'react';

		interface IAppContext {
			siteTitle: string;
		}

		interface IAppProvider {
			children: React.ReactNode;
		}

		export const AppContext = createContext<IAppContext>({} as IAppContext);

		export const AppProvider: React.FC<IAppProvider> = ({ children }) => {
			const siteTitle = 'Info Site';

			return (
				<AppContext.Provider
					value={{
						siteTitle
					}}
				>
					{children}
				</AppContext.Provider>
			);
		};		
		------------------------------------------
	- note that so far this code is the same we use in React sites
		- it is not in the /app directory since 
			- the /app directory is reserved to pages that will be in the routing system
			- we don't have a /src directory in Next and I don't want to put site files in the root directory with the config files, etc.
			- and at least technically AppContext is a component so I put it in the components directory
	- wrap App in AppProvider
		- in a React site, we would wrap the App component with AppProvider in the **main.tsx** file
		- in Next.js, we do this in the **pages/_app.tsx** file
			- if you don't have the pages directory of the _app.tsx file anymore, no problem, just recreate the directory and the file
		- **pages/_app.tsx**
			-------------------------------------------------
			import type { AppProps } from 'next/app';
			import { AppProvider } from '../components/AppContext';

			const App = ({ Component, pageProps }: AppProps) => {
				return (
					<>
						<AppProvider>
							<Component {...pageProps} />
						</AppProvider>
					</>
				);
			};

			export default App;		
			-------------------------------------------------
