- **what is GraphQL?**
	- GraphQL is an alternative way to REST which allows frontend clients to fetch data from the backend
	- the "QL" stands for Query Language which is something REST does not have
		- with REST, you send static requests to endpoints which at most allow you to specify one argument, e.g. `/employee/:id` which sends you back **every field** of every object
			- this often leads to front ends fetching much more data than they actually use, e.g. an array of employee objects each with 40 fields, when all the frontend displays are the firstName and lastName fields
		- **GraphQL allows the frontend to specify only the fields it needs**
			- this is the biggest advantage of GraphQL that you notice early on in using it
	- so GraphQL **gives frontends more flexibility** by allowing them to send queries to the backend specifying which records and fields they want instead of only being able to query static routes that often send them data they don't need##restvsgraphql
- **what we will do**
	- the purpose of this howto is to get people who have had no experience with GraphQL to the point where they have enough knowledge of it to employ it in a backend project
	- note that you can have both REST and GraphQL routes in a Node/Express application
		- you don't have to choose one or the other
		- you can simply add a graphql endpoint to your Node/Express backend (always `/graphql`) along with all of your REST endpoints, e.g. `/employees`, `employees:id`, etc.
			- use GraphQL for what it does best
				- allow flexible querying from the frontend 
			- use REST for what it does best
				- allow simple delivery of targeted data via a decicated enpoint
	- a common scenerio to learn GraphQL is to built it into your REST backend
		- continue to use to your REST end points as before
		- constantly experiment with using GraphQL queries to the GraphQL endpoint instead
	- this example uses the modern setup of TypeScript and ES6 modules on frontend (Vite) and backend (Node/Express/express-graphql)
- **background**
	- when getting into GraphQL, you are faced with quite a number of technology choices that can be confusing
	- in my short research of the subject, I found two major distinctions to understand
		- 1. **express-graphql vs Apollo Server**
			- **express-graphql** is a piece of middleware, to quickly setup a GraphQL Server, either with Express, or any web-framework that supports middleware
			- **Apollo Server** basically does the same thing, but has a large ecosystem that is installed with it which can do much more than express-graphql
			- it your goal is to have a lightweight GraphQL solution, Apollo is probably the worst pick
				- yet if you want to use the whole Apollo ecosystem, it might be the best pick
			- **note however** that even if you use **express-graphql** on the backend, it's recommended to use **apollo-client** on the frontend to send queries to the backend
		- 2. **buildSchema** vs **GraphQLObjectType**
			- buildSchema
				- very easy, quick way to set up GraphQL
				- apparently only for getting data
			- GraphQLObjectType
				- is more complicated
				- has many more options, e.g.
					- mutations
					- filters
	- other technologies to look at
		- [GraphQL-Yoga](https://the-guild.dev/graphql/yoga-server)
			- built with apollo-server and express-graphql. And it's built and maintained by the Prisma Team
		- [GraphQL Nexus](https://nexusjs.org)
			- uses auto-generation which will save you the time of creating GraphQL boilerplate to enable more complicated queries
		- [urql](https://formidable.com/open-source/urql)
			- an alternative to **Apollo Client** on the frontend
			- makes using GraphQL easier for features such as **uploading**, **authentication**, or if you are using **Next.js**
			- see: [Why I (finally) switched to urql from Apollo Client](https://blog.logrocket.com/why-i-finally-switched-to-urql-from-apollo-client)
