- **what we will do**
	- in this howto we will look at some common ways to debug JavaScript when working both in the **browser** and in **Node**
- **debugging in the browser**
	- it's common when solving problems in websites to want to know what the values of variables are at certain moments during the execution of your code
	- **console.log**
		- probably the most common way to find out the value of a variable is to simply output it to the terminal with `console.log()`
		- this works sufficiently well in most cases quite well particularly in smaller websites
		- example:
			- set up this site:
				- https://github.com/edwardtanguay/et003-consolelog
			- there's obviously a bug in it somewhere##thecolorpageijs
			- look through the files and get an understanding of the code of the site so you understand it
				- it's a classic Vanilla JavaScript/DOM site with modules
			- **tools.js**: the bug is in this file
				-------------------------------------------
				export const getTitle = () => {
					return 'Color Site';
				};

				export const insertColorsIntoElement = (elem) => {
					const colors = ['yellow', 'green', 'blue', 'purple', 'orange'];
					for (const color of colors) {
						const firstLetter = color.charAt(1).toUpperCase();
						const rest = color.slice(0);
						const titleColor = firstLetter + rest;
						const title = `${titleColor} Page`;
						elem.innerHTML += `<div class="colorBar" style="background-color: ${color}">${title}</div>`;
					}
				};
				-------------------------------------------
			- debug the code by displaying variable values with `console.log()`##andthelielilettting
			- eventually you'll solve the bug##evnsjeyou
			- for most cases `console.log` is **very useful** and **pragmatic** way to debug JavaScript in the browser which is why it is usually the only debugging tool many web developers use to display values variables
	- 3 tips for console.log()
		- in larger applications the amount of variable values in the console can get convoluted and confusing 
			- especially when you have **dozens or hundreds of output variables** in your console
			- particularly when the values are **large strings**
			- it's easy to lose the overview of which values belong to which variables
		- TIP 1: **console.log('message', message)**
			- pass the name of the variable as the first parameter
			- it's a bit more typing but for intensive debugging can be worth it##withlekkssi
		- TIP 2: **use the dev tools search**
			- you can also simply search any text including the named of the variables if you output them as the first parameter#gif#demofindtheletter
		- TIP 3: **console.log** and **console.debug**
			- sometimes when you are debugging, you have particular variables that are very large, e.g. when you output innerHTML
			- it is difficult to focus one on particular variable for a short time##havemanysjd
			- to fix this, change all the larger, less-needed variable to **console.debug**
			- then you can toggle the **Debug** option in the web developer tools#gif#demoshowclink
	- create a **custom logger**
		- don't forget that it is very easy to create a custom logger function called e.g. **debug()**
		- in larger applications when debugging becomes convoluted, I often quickly make a **dev.js** file with a **debug()** function:
			---------------------------------------
			export const debug = (label, value) => {
				console.log.bind(window.console);
				console.log(`>>> ${label.toUpperCase()} >>> [${value}]`);
			};
			---------------------------------------
		- I then import it in other files like this:
			------------------------------------
			import { debug } from './dev.js';
			------------------------------------
		- then use it like this:
			-------------------------------------
			debug('color', color);
			-------------------------------------
		- it's very simple and you can expand it and customize it to each application, sending large e.g. **user objects** to it which only print out the fields you want
		- you can add as many different debug functions as you want for various kinds of objects or variables
		- putting parameters around the values of strings help you catch preceding and trailing spaces##demotrailingsd
	- instead of displaying large objects in the console, display them on the browser page with **JSON.stringify()**
		- **tools.js**
			-----------------------------------------------
			export const insertColorsIntoElement = (elem) => {
				const colors = ['yellow', 'green', 'blue', 'purple', 'orange'];
				const titles = [];
				for (const color of colors) {
					const firstLetter = color.charAt(1).toUpperCase();
					const rest = color.slice(0);
					const titleColor = firstLetter + rest;
					const title = `${titleColor} Page`;
					elem.innerHTML += `<div class="colorBar" style="background-color: ${color}">${title}</div>`;
					titles.push(title);
				}

				const colorInfo = {};
				for (const color of colors) {
					colorInfo[color] = {
						randomId: Math.random(),
						allTitles: titles
					}
				}

				elem.innerHTML += '<pre>' + JSON.stringify(colorInfo, null, 2) + '</pre>';

				console.log(colorInfo);
			-----------------------------------------------
		- the third parameter is how many characters to indent
		- the objects with JSON.stringify are shown in their entirety and so can be perused and searched with ease
			- while the objects in the console are closed by default which you have to click open multiple times to read nested information##thetwosidisjggreen
		- I often use this with forms e.g. with an object variable named `formData` that contains all of the field values of my form
		- particularly in reactive frameworks such as React, Vue, Angular, etc. this will show you the values of your JavaScript objects as they change#gif#formshowdemofieldsss
	- debug by setting breakpoints and stepping through code in the **Debugger tab** of the your brower's Dev Tools
		- this is a completely different way to observe the values of your code as it executes
		- if you just need one value or a few values, using `console.log` might be faster
		- but particularly if you are debugging loops where one or more values are changing on every iteration, debugging with breakpoints is often more efficient
		- to stop execution at a specific point to view the values of variables
			- insert `debugger;` on the line on which you want to pause execution
			- it will stop on that line##demodefinkjsdddebb
			- you can hover over variables to see their values
			- you can enter a variable name on the right in order to **watch** its value change as you iterate through the loop#gif#demodefinkjsdddebb
			- note you can set new breakpoints#gif#demoandthenewpreak
	- a note on browsers	
		- when using devtool debugging, I find Chrome more useful than Firefox
			- e.g. objects that I am watching tend to stay open as I step through loops in Chrome, not so in Firefox
	- preemptive debugging
		- one way to debug more effectively is to debug less
			- i.e. use tools which catch errors before you have to debug them
		- use ES6 modules
			- ES6 modules are the modern way to develop JavaScript applications
			- one advantage is **ES6 modules are always in strict mode by default**
			- there is no need to write 'use strict;' at the top of your files
				- e.g. when using ES6 modules, if you forget `const` or `let`, then your code will not run##ifdemonothen
			- if you are not using ES6 modules in JavaScript for web development, e.g. if you are merely using one JavaScript file referenced by your HTML with no modules, then use `'use strict';` at the top of your JavaScript file so that the browser catches errors such as not using `const` or `var`##ifnoes6then
		- use TypeScript
			- TypeScript catches type errors as you develop, e.g. if you send a boolean variable to a function that expects a string
				- JavaScript will completely ignore these errors##jsplusts
			- furthermore, TypeScript will not build your project and will not deploy your code to production until you fix these errors##willnotbuilskjdf
			- particularly when creating websites, it is quick and easy to set up your projects in which TypeScript is completely configured to use
				- for JavaScript/DOM sites, use `npm create vite` then choose **Vanilla** and **TypeScript**
				- for React sites, use `npm create vite` then choose **React** and **TypeScript**#gif#dothecreatejs

