- the advantages of **JavaScript classes** and **class objects** over **object literals** in JavaScript
	- since ES6 in 2015, there are two kinds of objects in JavaScript
		- **object literals** - a simple object that has always been part of the language
		- **class objects** - an object instantiated from a JavaScript class (introduced with ES6)
	- with **object literals**, you can define methods
		- inside the method, the `this` keyword refers to the object
			-------------------------------------------------
			const person1 = {
				firstName: "Lena",
				lastName: "Weber",
				sayHello: function () {
					console.log(`Hello, my name is ${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`);
				}
			};

			console.log(person1);
			-------------------------------------------------
	- however, you realize after awhile that this is **not very useful in practice**
		- if you have e.g. having numerous person objects with methods that perform the same function, you have unnecessary code repetition:
			----------------------------------------------------
			const person1 = {
			  firstName: "Lena",
			  lastName: "Weber",
			  sayHello: function() {
				console.log(`Hello, my name is ${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`);
			  }
			};

			const person2 = {
			  firstName: "Matthias",
			  lastName: "Schneider",
			  sayHello: function() {
				console.log(`Hello, my name is ${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`);
			  }
			};

			person1.sayHello(); 
			person2.sayHello(); 		
			----------------------------------------------------
	- before ES6 in 2015, this problem was solved with a concept called **prototype** in JavaScript
		- but ES6 introduced **JavaScript classes** which uses prototype to give the developer the ability to program with object-oriented patterns as one does in languages such as C#, Java, PHP, etc.
		- here is a more realistic example of the above code using **JavaScript classes**
		- we have numerous people for which we need to generate a nametag text:
			------------------------------------------------------------
			class Person {

				constructor(firstName, lastName) {
					this.firstName = firstName;
					this.lastName = lastName;
				}

				getNametagText = () => {
					return `Hello, my name is ${this.firstName} ${this.lastName}`;
				};
			}

			const person1 = new Person('Lena', 'Weber');
			const person2 = new Person('Matthias', 'Schneider');

			console.log(person1.getNametagText());
			console.log(person2.getNametagText());		
			------------------------------------------------------------
		- now, the method is not in **every object** but instead in the **class** which is used to create the objects 
			- no matter how many persons we create, we only have one method
			- this method can be changed in one place which effects all objects instantiated from that class
	- there are many more advantages of **JavaScript classes and objects** instead of plain **object literals**
		- you can use most basic features of OOP such as
			- inheritance
			- method overloading
		- you can use most [OOP patterns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_Patterns) which help you more easily solve complex programming tasks 
		- you learn skills that enable you to more easily learn the **Angular** framework, which uses **JavaScript classes** by default
		- you learn skills which are easily transferable to OOP languages such as C#, Java and PHP
