- when you use object literal bracket notation in TypeScript
	- TypeScript needs to know the type of property depending on the property sent it
	- but since this is dynamic, you need a bit more complex type definition, namely:
		- property is of type **T**
		- value is of type e.g. **IUser[T]**
		- and you define T in a generic statement as **<T extends keyof IUser>**
			-----------------------------------------------
			interface IUser {
				firstName: string;
				lastName: string;
				age: number
			}

			const changeProperty = <T extends keyof IUser>(user: IUser, prop: T, value: IUser[T]) => {
				user[prop] = value;
			}

			const user: IUser = {
				firstName: 'Hans',
				lastName: 'Lefèbvre',
				age: 23
			};

			changeProperty(user, "firstName", "Georg");

			console.log(user);		
