- **(4) pre-2015 solution: use a callback to asynchronously get data that is asynchronously fetched in a function**
	- the problem with the above solution is that
		- the funtion simply **begins** to fetch the data
		- immedately sends **nothing back** (undefined)
		- then **9 milliseconds later** it gets its data and returns it to nowhere (!)
	- change the function so it accepts a callback function which is called when the asynchronously fetched data is available
		- **dataLoader.ts**
			----------------------------------------------
			export const getAsynchronousCallbackEmployees = (callback) => {
				const url = 'https://edwardtanguay.vercel.app/share/employees.json';
				(async () => {
					const employees = (await axios.get(url)).data
					console.log('async', employees);
					callback(employees);
				})();
			}			
			----------------------------------------------
		- don't worry about the TypeScript error for now
			- the JavaScript in the browser will still work, and there is enough to understand at the moment##tehtypesderr
	- now from main, send a callback function as a parameter, inside of which employees will be defined
		- **main.ts**
			-------------------------------------------
			dataLoader.getAsynchronousCallbackEmployees((asychronousCallbackEmloyees) => {
			  console.log('main', asychronousCallbackEmloyees);
			});			
			-------------------------------------------
		- now when the page reloads, you will see that 
			- 1. first the async data is available in the **function** 
			- 2. **1 millisecond later** it is available in **main**##thenonesedss
